In React, a common pattern for building user interfaces is to separate components into two types: presentational components and container components.

A **Presentational Component** is a component that is primarily focused on how things look. It typically receives data and callbacks as props, and it uses them to render a UI. Presentational components are usually stateless, meaning they don't manage any state of their own, and they don't have any side effects.

Here's an example of a presentational component:
```javascript
function Button(props) {
  return (
    <button onClick={props.onClick}>
      {props.label}
    </button>
  );
}
```
In this example, the `Button` component is focused on rendering a button element with a label and an `onClick` handler. It receives the label and onClick function as props and doesn't manage any state of its own.

A **Container Component** is a component that is primarily focused on how things work. It typically manages state and side effects, and it passes down data and callbacks to presentational components as props. Container components are usually stateful, meaning they manage their own state or the state of child components.

Here's an example of a container component:
```kotlin
class ButtonContainer extends React.Component {
  constructor(props) {
    super(props);
    this.state = { count: 0 };
  }

  handleClick() {
    this.setState({ count: this.state.count + 1 });
  }

  render() {
    return (
      <Button label={`Clicked ${this.state.count} times`} onClick={this.handleClick.bind(this)} />
    );
  }
}
```
In this example, the `ButtonContainer` component is focused on managing the state of the button and passing it down to the `Button` presentational component as a prop. It manages its own state using the `count` property, and it has a `handleClick` method that updates the state when the button is clicked.

In summary, presentational components are focused on how things look and don't manage any state or side effects, while container components are focused on how things work and manage state and side effects. Separating your components in this way can make your code more modular, easier to reason about, and more reusable.

