Sure, to allow the tooltip to be closed by clicking the button again, we can modify the `handleButtonClick` function to toggle the active tooltip based on whether the `activeTooltip` value matches the `tooltipRef` or not. Here's the updated code for the `Tooltip` component:
```jsx
import { useEffect, useRef } from 'react';
import { useTooltipContext } from './TooltipContext';

export function Tooltip({ children, content }) {
  const { activeTooltip, setActiveTooltip } = useTooltipContext();
  const tooltipRef = useRef(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    function handleClickOutside(event) {
      if (tooltipRef.current && !tooltipRef.current.contains(event.target)) {
        setActiveTooltip(null);
      }
    }

    if (activeTooltip) {
      document.addEventListener('mousedown', handleClickOutside);
      return () => {
        document.removeEventListener('mousedown', handleClickOutside);
      };
    }
  }, [activeTooltip, setActiveTooltip]);

  useEffect(() => {
    if (activeTooltip) {
      tooltipRef.current.focus();
    }
  }, [activeTooltip]);

  function handleClick(event) {
    event.stopPropagation();
  }

  function handleButtonClick(event) {
    event.stopPropagation();
    setActiveTooltip(activeTooltip === tooltipRef ? null : tooltipRef);
  }

  return (
    <>
      <div>
        <button onClick={handleButtonClick}>{children}</button>
      </div>
      {activeTooltip === tooltipRef && (
        <div ref={tooltipRef} tabIndex={0} onClick={handleClick}>
          {content}
        </div>
      )}
    </>
  );
}
```
In this updated code, we modify the `handleButtonClick` function to toggle the active tooltip based on whether the `activeTooltip` value matches the `tooltipRef` or not. If the two values match, then we set the `activeTooltip` to `null` to close the tooltip. Otherwise, we set the `activeTooltip` to `tooltipRef` to open the tooltip.

With this modification, clicking the button when the tooltip is already active will close the tooltip, and clicking the button again will reopen the tooltip.

